AmbDescription:
Please keep your RSVP as up-to-date as possible! We've had numbers close to requiring a Boulder County group permit for this location before, so having a head count ahead of time is helpful so that we have time to apply for a permit if needed üôÇ
Plan to arrive by 8:45 or earlier, we will be hitting the trail by 9:00am sharp! We will plan on meeting at the main Lagerman Reservoir parking area, overflow parking available at the intersection of Pike and 75th. We will do a round of introductions for all people and dogs before we head out.
Route options include the 5-mile Open Sky Loop, with shorter distances available for those interested! We typically have a longer distance group and a shorter-distance group.
Terrain: This is an on-leash restricted area, bikes are allowed, but it is typically pretty quiet. Mostly flat gravel/dirt, some rolling hills. Wide enough trail to talk and meet new people at conversation pace!
Beginners are welcome, we may have some extra bungee lines, belts, etc... At a minimum, have a non-restrictive harness for your dog and ideally a bungee leash. In a pinch, a climbing harness can help you get a feel for the sport!
We want to make this an inclusive sport for all dogs, we do frequently have some shy and also dog reactive dogs participating. We have a color-coded bandana system to help all dogs and runners feel comfortable. Please do not allow dogs to great each other unless you have permission from owners first!
Hope to see you there!

AmbDescription:
Come join us for a trail run and learn about the sport of canicross! 

We will meet at the parking lot off of Ring Road across from the Elizabethtown Nature Park. We will be doing an out and back of the unpaved trail on the eastern side of the lake, approximately 4 miles. All skill levels and speeds welcome, you can do as much or as little of the route as you would like. Please keep your and your dog‚Äôs physical limitations and current fitness level in mind when participating. You do not need to be a NACC member to participate. 

Since this is intended to be an opportunity to learn about canicross it is not necessary to have a full canicross setup. However, no flexi-leashes, face halters, or ‚Äúno-pull‚Äù harnesses will be allowed. A non-restrictive Y-front harness is preferred along with a bungee leash if available. Dogs must be 12 months or older for their safety. 

NACC has a strict ‚ÄúNo greet‚Äù policy for the safety of all participating dogs. Please do not let your dog approach other dogs or humans and provide space if passing on the trail. 

You must sign a waiver if you haven't done so before: https://nacanicross.fillout.com/t/dQrpDEnWaEus.

Your dog is required to be ON LEASH at all times. No exceptions. 

Be sure to clean up after yourself and your dog. 

What is canicross?
Canicross is running cross country with your dog. The difference between canicross and just regular trail running your dog, is that canicross is powered by the dog! Special harnesses are used to allow the dog to have optimal and comfortable pulling. Dogs are connected by a bungee lead: no longer than 6 feet, which is then attached to a special running belt on their owner. The belt and bungee lead allow for shock absorbency and keep the owner from any back injury. The dog may be pulling, but the owner is the driver! Dogs are taught special commands for things like "left", "right", "slow down", "speed up" etc. The goal is to work as a team to get to the finish line!

What is North American Canicross (NACC)?
North American Canicross (NACC) was founded in June of 2019 for the purpose of promoting Canicross as a competitive sport in the United States. North American Canicross‚Äô program includes the LIFETIME ACHIEVED MILES, RACE DOG DISTANCE, and CHAMPIONSHIP TITLES which have similar structures, but different competition standards for the canicross enthusiast. All events are open to any and all persons without discrimination who shall exhibit good sportsmanship and uphold the standards set forth in these rules and regulations. All breeds and skill levels welcome! Teams must be registered in order to compete in North American Canicross events and titling programs. Find out more about registering your team and the titling program at https://nacanicross.com/about.

COME RUN WITH US!
WHAT IS CANICROSS?
Canicross, or cross-country trail running with dogs, came about when the dog sledding community needed a way to cross-train their teams in the off-season. Because of this, the original canicross dogs were primarily traditional mushing breeds. The popularity of canicross as a stand-alone sport has led to a significant increase in breed variety, now including pure and mixed breeds of all shapes and sizes! What sets canicross apart from regular trail running with your dog is that canicross is powered by the dog! Special harnesses are used to allow the dog to have optimal and comfortable pulling. They are connected by a bungee lead‚Äîno longer than 9 feet when fully extended‚Äîwhich is then attached to a special running belt on their owner. The belt and bungee lead allow for shock absorbency and protect the owner from back injury. The dog may be pulling, but the owner is the driver! Dogs are taught special commands for things like "left", "right", "slow down", "speed up" etc. The objective is for the owner and dog to work as a team to reach the finish line!
WHO IS NACC?
North American Cancross (NACC) was founded in June of 2019 for the purpose of promoting Canicross as a competitive sport in the United States. Canicross is meant to highlight the fundamental elements of a dog and human running team: strength, confidence, speed, communication and all around athleticism. NACC events seeks to maintain and promote the highest standards for competition in canicross for dog and human running teams and canine sports enthusiasts at all different levels. NACC's standards for competition purposes are to ensure a safe activity for dogs when properly conditioned for the demands of the sport.
nacanicross.com

AmbDescription:
I am putting an invite on the calendar for a canicross run at McKnight Lake Trail! One of my favorite foresty/lake trails.This is in Chaska MN, and the run is about 3.5 miles 

All skill levels and speeds are welcome, you can do as much or as little of the route as you would like. Please keep you and your dog‚Äôs physical limitations and current fitness level in mind when participating. You do not need to be a NACC member to participate.

Since this is intended to be an opportunity to learn about canicross it is not necessary to have a full canicross setup. A non-restrictive Y-front harness is preferred along with a bungee leash if available. 
I had extras though so let me know if ya want to try everything! 

NACC has a strict ‚ÄúNo greet‚Äù policy. Please do not let your dog approach other dogs or humans and provide space if passing on the trail. 

You must sign a waiver if you haven't done so before: https://nacanicross.fillout.com/t/dQrpDEnWaEus.

Your dog is required to be ON LEASH at all times. No exceptions. 

Be sure to clean up after yourself and your dog. 

What is canicross?
Canicross is running cross country with your dog. The difference between canicross and just regular trail running your dog, is that canicross is powered by the dog! Special harnesses are used to allow the dog to have optimal and comfortable pulling. Dogs are connected by a bungee lead: no longer than 6 feet, which is then attached to a special running belt on their owner. The belt and bungee lead allow for shock absorbency and keep the owner from any back injury. The dog may be pulling, but the owner is the driver! Dogs are taught special commands for things like "left", "right", "slow down", "speed up" etc. The goal is to work as a team to get to the finish line!

What is North American Canicross (NACC)?
North American Canicross (NACC) was founded in June of 2019 for the purpose of promoting Canicross as a competitive sport in the United States. North American Canicross‚Äô program includes the LIFETIME ACHIEVED MILES, RACE DOG DISTANCE, and CHAMPIONSHIP TITLES which have similar structures, but different competition standards for the canicross enthusiast. All events are open to any and all persons without discrimination who shall exhibit good sportsmanship and uphold the standards set forth in these rules and regulations. All breeds and skill levels welcome! Teams must be registered in order to compete in North American Canicross events and titling programs. Find out more about registering your team and the titling program at https://nacanicross.com/about. 

Please come, bring friends with or without dogs.

Parking : head toward the beach, when you reach the fork, turn right and go all the way to the end (near H on park map)

The State Park requires a recreation passport or day use fee

MEET UP DETAILS
This meet up is open to any interested parties, but is specifically planned for teams entering Iron Paws. 
Iron Paws is a virtual 7 stage race where you compete as an individual team and (new this year) a pack made up of 5-10 teams. For more information please see :
https://www.facebook.com/share/g/15VAJYzJJJ/?mibextid=wwXIfr


WHAT IS CANICROSS?
Canicross, or cross-country trail running with dogs, came about when the dog sledding community needed a way to cross-train their teams in the off-season. Because of this, the original canicross dogs were primarily traditional mushing breeds. The popularity of canicross as a stand-alone sport has led to a significant increase in breed variety, now including pure and mixed breeds of all shapes and sizes! What sets canicross apart from regular trail running with your dog is that canicross is powered by the dog! Special harnesses are used to allow the dog to have optimal and comfortable pulling. They are connected by a bungee lead‚Äîno longer than 9 feet when fully extended‚Äîwhich is then attached to a special running belt on their owner. The belt and bungee lead allow for shock absorbency and protect the owner from back injury. The dog may be pulling, but the owner is the driver! Dogs are taught special commands for things like "left", "right", "slow down", "speed up" etc. The objective is for the owner and dog to work
as a team to reach the finish line!

WHO IS NACC?
North American Cancross (NACC) was founded in June of 2019 for the purpose of promoting Canicross as a competitive sport in the United States. Canicross is meant to highlight the fundamental elements of a dog and human running team: strength, confidence, speed, communication and all around athleticism. NACC events seeks to maintain and promote the highest standards for competition in canicross for dog and human running teams and canine sports enthusiasts at all different levels. NACC's standards for competition purposes are to ensure a safe activity for dogs when properly conditioned for the demands of the sport.

AmbDescription:
We are headed back to the Foothills! If you are planning on attending, please keep a close eye on event updates, since in the case of heavy snow we will move the meetup location to Lagerman Reservoir in Longmont. Please also keep your RSVP up to date, we've had some meetup attendance numbers approaching the level where we would need group permits (yay!). RSVPs help us plan in the even that we need to apply for a permit ahead of time.
Plan to arrive 8:45 or earlier, we will be hitting the trail by 9:00am sharp. There are several parking areas, so we will plan on meeting up at the picnic shelter in the map posted in the discussion. Multiple distances possible, there is a 3-mile and also a 6.5+ mile loop, shorter-out-and-backs also possible.
Terrain: This is an on-leash area, no mountain bikes are allowed on Saturdays. Rolling, hilly terrain, not as flat as some of our other meetups and at a higher elevation. Trees/shade, some more open areas. "Mountain vistas, views of golden plains, scenic trails, diverse habitats, and a rich heritage make Betasso Preserve a favorite destination in the foothills."
Beginners are very welcome, we always have a few extra bungee lines, belts, etc... If you are interested in investing in gear but are unsure on sizing you can ask people for help or to try on their gear. At a minimum please have a non-restrictive harness, y-shaped harness for your dog and ideally a bungee leash and waist-belt.
We want to make this an inclusive sport for all dogs, we do frequently have some shy or reactive dogs participating. Please do not allow dogs to great each other unless you have permission from owners first. Keep your leashes at a manageable length and respect everyone‚Äôs space. We will also use a bandana system to indicate dog‚Äôs social level.
[https://bouldercounty.gov/.../parks-and.../betasso-preserve/](https://bouldercounty.gov/.../parks-and.../betasso-preserve/?fbclid=IwZXh0bgNhZW0CMTAAAR3JnEyQTx67laxbuKcx-moGZiMspwxqQxtlXvIr7PPHhlEnamooyQjhZ4Q_aem_-0GdPyzjNMkV32nP9eFAEA)

AmbDescription:
Do you like running? Do you like dogs? Then canicross is for you!

If you'd like to know more or have been running with your canine companion for years, come join us for a canicross meet up. Learn about the sport in an EXTREMELY low stakes environment. For this meet up, we will meet at the Mead‚Äôs Quarry parking lot at IJAMs. Runners will gather by the public restrooms next to River Sports. There is plenty of parking by the quarry and paid parking by the visitor‚Äôs center. 

What to expect?
We will be running with our canine companions. No worries, this will be a casual jog on the Tharp Trace Trail (only 1 mile and we can do more for the super adventurous). Canicross requires a non-restrictive harness and bungee lead. We can teach you more about gear, but you can bring any non-restrictive harness and lead. Please note that dogs under 12 months are not permitted. We will be trail running so humans should wear durable running shoes and comfortable clothes, and bring hydration for your running pal.

We practice a no-greet policy. Some dogs might be spicy or simply not want to play. Please make sure your dog is leashed at all times.

AmbDescription:
Open to runners with dogs (harnessed and leashed) as well as those interested explicitly in the sport of Canicross!

This is a "no greet" meet up, but please feel free to add / message me if you're concerned about proximity of dogs.

We will pace appropriately for the slowest team, so if you are new or don't fancy yourself a fast runner, please don't hesitate to come out (I myself have been hiking more than running, so this will be far from a PR event! üòÇ) 

COME RUN WITH US!
WHAT IS CANICROSS?
Canicross, or cross-country trail running with dogs, came about when the dog sledding community needed a way to cross-train their teams in the off-season. Because of this, the original canicross dogs were primarily traditional mushing breeds. The popularity of canicross as a stand-alone sport has led to a significant increase in breed variety, now including pure and mixed breeds of all shapes and sizes! What sets canicross apart from regular trail running with your dog is that canicross is powered by the dog! Special harnesses are used to allow the dog to have optimal and comfortable pulling. They are connected by a bungee lead-no longer than 9 feet when fully extended-which is then attached to a special running belt on their owner. The belt and bungee lead allow for shock absorbency and protect the owner from back injury. The dog may be pulling, but the owner is the driver! Dogs are taught special commands for things like "left"
", "right", "slow down",
"speed up" etc. The objective is for the owner and dog to work
as a team to reach the finish line!
WHO IS NACC?
North American Cancross (NACC) was founded in June of 2019 for the purpose of promoting Canicross as a competitive sport in the United States. Canicross is meant to highlight the fundamental elements of a dog and human running team: strength, confidence, speed, communication and all around athleticism. NACC events seeks to maintain and promote the highest standards for competition in canicross for dog and human running teams and canine sports enthusiasts at all different levels. NACC's standards for competition purposes are to ensure a safe activity for dogs when properly conditioned for the demands of the sport.

AmbDescription:
Join us for a run with our dogs!

Canicross is the sport of trail running while attached to your dog. Dogs typically wear non-restrictive harnesses attached via a bungee line to the human's waist belt.

I will have some canicross gear for new folks to try out!  Although specialized canicross gear is not required to participate, we ask that your dog is leashed and under control. Flexi leashes, gentle leaders, and no-pull harnesses are not allowed at North American Canicross events. 

For safety, dog-dog greetings are not allowed at NACC meetups. This means we don't allow dogs to greet face to face and dogs who don't know each other need to maintain a minimum distance of six feet.

Trail description:¬†Meet at Latte Nature Preserve in the first lot after the gates (see map).  There are bathrooms in this parking lot! The trail is 3-4 miles and the terrain is all wide, packed dirt paths after a very short distance on the road to get to the path.

Snacks (and doggy treats) await us back in the parking lot!

AmbDescription:
Drop in Training / Capitolina Dryland Preview
Come join us for a casual weekly meet up at the GE Trails to get in whatever kind of training your team needs. There are 11 miles of trails through shady forest to train on, and they all loop within a small area. This is a great park to switch dogs out as everything loops back to the parking lot. Parking is secure but there is no water, shade, or facilities on site so plan accordingly. As it cools off, most of the trails are suitable for bikejor too if you incorporate that with your running. This is the site of the Capitolina Dryland Challenge in January, and I can point you towards the race route if you want to preview. If you have any particular training needs or are just getting started and want to talk gear or starting a dog, we can always do that - just let me know!

AmbDescription:
Hello everyone! Hope you are enjoying winter! It is time we got out onto the trail as a pack and did some winter running! Cone join me as we take over Lake Anna State Park! 

We will meet at the Sawtooth trail head parking lot. We will follow the Sawtooth trail and Turkey Run trail in a loop to make up an estimated 3.5 mile course. The trail is single track through the woods. Make sure to were trail shoes if you have them as there will be roots, leaves and rocks. The trails are usually clear to run without issue. This is a relatively flat course but follows the Lake and is just beautiful and quiet in winter. 

All fitness levels are encouraged to attend. Please let me know if you want to do some harness try on as I will bring my try on kit. 

If your dog is reactive please let me know so we can make accommodation. 

As always please come prepared to pick up after your dog. 

I look forward to seeing you all!

AmbDescription:
Come join us for a canicross trail run and canihike!
Meetup is two events in one, both starting from the Wolf River Greenway Shady Grove Trailhead. All paces and beginner trail runners are welcome!
We meet almost every week on Sunday morning, so feel free to join us regularly!
The 7:00 am start will be a canicross trail run on the Wolf River White/Blue Trail. We will run approximately 4.5 miles at an easy pace.
At 9am, we will hike/walk approximately 2-3 miles on the Blue/Yellow trail for those that simply want a canihike or walking pace.
The Wolf River Trails are flat, non-technical trails located in the Lucius Burch State Natural Area at Shelby Farms Park, and a great place for beginners and experienced runners/hikers alike. The parking lot should have plenty of parking early in the morning, but fills up fast. There is additional parking at the office building across the street. Feel free to reach out with any questions.

AmbDescription:
Join us Saturday morning at Los Penasquitos Canyon Preserve for a 4 to 7 mile trail run, your choice. Start is at 8:00 am. Come early to gear-up!
\*Trail is flat, and has a varied terrain surface.
\*Trail has wide & narrow sections.
\*Trail is groomed, except creek areas with river rocks. Watch your steps!
\*Trail is partly shaded & partly not! Bring Water.
\*Trail features shady creeks, ponds & waterfall

HOW TO FIND US:
FROM BLACK MOUNTAIN ROAD AT TRAFFIC LIGHT INTERSECTION - TURN ONTO CANYONSIDE PARK DRIVEWAY INTO CANYONSIDE COMMUNITY PARK
- GO TO THE FAR WEST PARKING LOT ADJACENT TO THE WEST BASEBALL FIELD, BEFORE THE RANCH HOUSE.
- TRAILHEAD STARTS THERE.

DOWNLOAD THE "ALL TRAIL" MAP - LOS PENASQUITOS CANYON TRAIL
https://www.alltrails.com/trail/us/california/los-penasquitos-canyon-trail
DO NOT MEET AT THE GREEN/BLACK DOT ON MAP!!
MEET AT FAR WEST PARKING LOT INSIDE THE CANYONSIDE COMMUNITY PARK

Photos & videos are taken during all events. It's your responsibility to inform everyone if you do not want your photo taken or to participate in event videos.

Remember to "Cancel" if you decide not to attend.

FYI: Canicross running is best performed in temperatures cooler than 68 degrees to avoid heat exhaustion in dogs, if temps are warmer than 71 degrees the meetup will be considered cancelled, for the health of the dogs.

Please read all below.
Suggested Equipment & what to bring:

Canicross Belt or Runner's Hands-free belt.
Dog Harness with back leash attachment.
No "run-restricted" harnesses.
1. Dog Leash or Canicross Bungee leash.
2. Water & Treats - For you & your dog.
3. Bring your own canine first aid kit.
4. Wag Bags
5. Rabies shot & dog license must be current.

\*Please, no dogs under one year old. Their bodies are not fully developed yet and need a bit more time to grow before pulling in a harness.
\*\*\*Not Recommended for Dogs with shorter muzzles, i.e Pit Bulls, Boxers, etc. May not be well suited for canicross running, because of strained breathing issues & heart stress.
\*\*\*We're here for low stress fun for Owners and their dogs! try to maintain a 6FT distance from each other.
\*\*\*Should your dog show signs of aggression towards other dogs or humans, you'll be asked to leave.
\*\*\*Protect the safety of dogs and their human teammates at the meet-up at all times. If your dog damages another dog or person, YOU are responsible for any damages & medical bills to the wounded party.
